msDesc.head: Gregory the Great, Homilies on Ezechiel

summary.seg: The Benedictine cathedral priory of Christ Church Canterbury possessed one of the great libraries of medieval England. There survive today well over two hundred manuscripts, as well as some early printed books, that are known to have been part of this collection. This copy of Gregory the Great's Homilies on Ezechiel is one such survival, and one of twenty Christ Church books held at Cambridge University Library. It is one of two copies of the text known to have been at Christ Church; the other is now Windsor, St George's Chapel, MS 5.

CUL MS Ff.3.9 was made in the late eleventh or twelfth century. The date of other surviving copies of this text indicates that it was little-known in England prior to the Norman Conquest, but that copies multiplied quickly thereafter. It may have been made at Christ Church itself, where it was to spend the next four or so centuries. However, Neil Ker has pointed to the close connections that must have existed at this time between Christ Church and Rochester cathedral priories - Ralph d'Escures, former bishop of Rochester, was archbishop at Canterbury 1114-22, while Ernulf, former prior of Canterbury, was bishop of Rochester 1115-24 - concluding that 'It is a priori likely that the Christ Church collection contained manuscripts which the Rochester monks copied in this period and perhaps to a lesser extent earlier.' Gregory's Homilies on Ezechiel is one of fourteen patristic texts to have existed in copies at both Christ Church and Rochester, and where these copies are known to have survived (the Rochester copy of the Homilies is now London, British Library, Royal MS 4 B i ).

According to C.R. Dodwell, the same artist was responsible for the decorated initials in both MS Ff.3.9 and Cambridge, Trinity College, MS B.5.28 , and later scholarship has considered the production to be English (whether or not they are by the same hand). That Norman artists were also at work in Canterbury at this time, however, is shown by Cambridge, Corpus Christi College, MS 291 : although the initials in CUL MS Ff.3.9 and Trinity MS B.5.28 also feature bright, hard colours and foliage and beast heads, those in Corpus MS 291 draw on Norman antecedents independent of Anglo-Saxon traditions of ornamental initials and were therefore likely executed by a Norman artist, working at the nearby abbey of St Augustine (see Morgan and Panayotova (2013) and Gameson (1995) for further details).

Dr James Freeman
Medieval Manuscripts Specialist
Cambridge University Library

foliation.note: Numbering in pencil in the upper right-hand corner of the rectos.

list.item: Quire 138-2 (ff. 97-102: 7th and 8th leaves after f. 102 excised, probably blank)

collation.signatures: Medieval quire signatures in ink, Roman numerals on the verso of the last leaf of the quire, from Quire 'III' (f. 24v) onwards.

supportDesc.condition: The manuscript is in good condition overall, however the decorated initial on f. 2r has been rubbed and creased resulting in the loss of some pigment.

layout.seg: Ruled in hardpoint, in a single column, frame only (except for a few leaves at the beginning of the volume, where lines are ruled as well), 39 lines to the page, written above top line.

handNote.p: Caroline minuscule, by perhaps two hands.

handDesc.handNote: Rubrics, headings and opening lines of text written in rustic capitals, in red or black ink.

decoNote.p: Eleven- or twelve-line initials in blue, entwined in scrolls of green, orange and rose foliage, hybrid creatures and a human head on red or red and blue ground, at the (ff. 2r, 56r).
Seven-line initial in red, with red floral patterns on green ground (f. 1r).
Four- to ten-line initials in blue, green and red, at chapter divisions.
Two-line initials in red within the text.

note.p: Annotations throughout the volume, in plummet and ink, by hands of the 12th-15th centuries, presumably by the monks of Christ Church Cathedral Priory in Canterbury. There are also present the 'ice-cream cone' style of marginal markings commonly found in manuscripts from Christ Church library (see ff. 25v, 56r-58r).

Scattered annotations in pencil by a 17th-century hand, perhaps that of Wheelocke, Abraham, 1593-1653 Abraham Wheelocke (see, for example, ff. 12r, 13r, 14v-18r, 19v and elsewhere, throughout the manuscript).
Note of the contents added by an unidentified 18th-century hand (front pastedown).
Collation formula written on the rear pastedown by H.L. Pink.

binding.p: Blind-tooled speckled calfskin (17th/18th century), with blind-tooled three-line fillet along the edges. Rebacked. Repaired by Douglas Cockerell and SonDouglas Cockerell and Son (Firm), Grantchester, May 1966.

history.origin:
Late 11th / 12th century. England, probably Canterbury, at Christ Church Cathedral Priory, Canterbury Christ Church Priory (Canterbury, England) , but perhaps at Rochester Cathedral Priory Rochester Cathedral Priory .
The manuscript is dated to the late 11th century by Gneuss, Gameson and Dodwell, and to the 12th century by Ker.

provenance.p:
1r: Pressmark 'TR' (in monogram form), characteristic of manuscripts belonging to
Christ Church Cathedral Priory, Canterbury Christ Church Priory (Canterbury, England) in the 12th century. (See: James, The Ancient Libraries of Canterbury and Dover The Catalogues of the Libraries of Christ Church Priory and St. Augustine's Abbey at Canterbury and of St. Martin's Priory at Dover (Cambridge: at the University Press, 1903), pp. xxxi-xxxv).

Marginal markings characteristic of manuscripts belonging to Christ Church Christ Church Priory (Canterbury, England) : 'ice cream cone', diagonal arrangement of dots, sometimes with descending lines of dots alongside the text.

Recorded in the list of books at Christ Church Christ Church Priory (Canterbury, England) , compiled during the time of Prior Henry of Eastry (Prior 1284-1331). No. 144 in M.R. James's edition (see: James, Ancient Libraries , pp. 32, 507).

Recorded in the list compiled by William Ingram, custos of the shrine of St Thomas, of books repaired at Christ Church Christ Church Priory (Canterbury, England) in 1508. No. 130 in M.R. James's edition (see: James, Ancient Libraries , pp. 157, 507).
One of the manuscripts of Richard Holdsworth (1590-1649), Master of Emmanuel College Holdsworth, Richard, 1590-1649 .

history.acquisition: Acquired by the University Library in July 1664: no. 56 in the inventory of Holdsworth's manuscripts compiled by William Crowe (MS Ff.4.27 / Dd.8.45) (number written on f. i recto).

recordHist.source: This catalogue entry draws on the description provided by Paul Binski and Patrick Zutshi, with the collaboration of Stella Panayotova, Western Illuminated Manuscripts: A Catalogue of the Collection in Cambridge University Library (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2011) (used here by kind permission of Cambridge University Press), and an unpublished description of the manuscript composed between 1947 and 1970 by H.L. Pink, now held in the University Archives (ULIB 7/3/75).

availability.p: Entry to read in the Library is permitted only on presentation of a valid reader's card. For information on eligibility and admissions procedures, see Joining the Library). For further information on the availability of the manuscript, please contact the Manuscripts Reading Room.
